      {
        "heading":"Who Is This Study For?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"People who struggle with assurance",
            "body" :"If you find yourself wondering whether you are really a Christian — whether your faith is genuine, whether God truly accepts you, whether you really belong to him — this letter was written for you. 1 John is not a test designed to produce anxiety. John states his purpose plainly at the end: 'I have written these things to you who believe in the name of the Son of God so that you may know that you have eternal life' (5:13). The goal is confidence, not doubt."
          },

          {
            "title":"People unsettled by false teaching",
            "body" :"John wrote into a specific crisis: people had left the community, and their departure had shaken those who remained. If you have ever been confused by confident-sounding teaching that seemed to undermine what you believed, or by Christians who seemed more certain and more impressive but whose message felt subtly different, this letter speaks directly to that experience."
          },

          {
            "title":"People who want to go deeper in 1 John",
            "body" :"The letter is only five chapters long, but it is theologically rich and structurally complex. This study moves through it carefully, paying attention to what John actually says in context rather than lifting out familiar verses in isolation. Whether you are new to 1 John or have read it many times, working through it closely is likely to surface things you have not noticed before."
          }
        ]
      },

      {
        "heading":"Individual or Group Study?",
        "blocks" :[
          {
            "title":"On your own",
            "body" :"This study works well as a personal study. Each session begins with a prompt to read the relevant passage — take that seriously, since the questions are designed to reward close attention to John's actual words. Write your answers as you go, and give the reflection questions at the end real time. 1 John rewards slow, attentive reading more than speed."
          },

          {
            "title":"In a group",
            "body" :"The study works well in a small group setting. The most rewarding approach is usually for each person to work through the session individually first, writing their answers, and then for the group to come together to compare what they found. The themes of light, love, and assurance generate rich discussion — and because John's letter was written to a community, reading it together has a particular fittingness."
          },

